## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of backpressure, bounded buffers, and graceful shutdown in a concurrent environment using asynchronous primitives.

## Key Concepts
- Bounded buffers and backpressure
- Multiple producers and multiple consumers
- Graceful shutdown signaling
- Correct testing under varying rates

## Code Example
```javascript
class BoundedQueue {
  constructor(capacity) {
    this.capacity = capacity
    this.queue = []
    this.waitPuts = []
    this.waitGets = []
  }
  async push(item) {
    if (this.queue.length < this.capacity) {
      this.queue.push(item)
      if (this.waitGets.length) this.waitGets.shift()(this.queue.shift())
      return
    }
    await new Promise(res => this.waitPuts.push(res))
    return this.push(item)
  }
  async pop() {
    if (this.queue.length) {
      const item = this.queue.shift()
      if (this.waitPuts.length) this.waitPuts.shift()
      return item
    }
    return new Promise(resolve => this.waitGets.push(resolve))
  }
}
// Usage sketch: create producers/consumers using q.push(q.pop())
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt for a single consumer vs multiple consumers?
- What strategies exist if you must drop data when the buffer is full, and how would you test them?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to design a low-level concurrent router with per-producer ordering, a bounded queue, and a controlled degradation path using sampling. It demonstrates practical handling of backpressure and fairness without requiring large-scale infrastructure.

## Key Concepts
- **Per-agent FIFO buffers** preserve ordering for each producer
- **Global bounded queue** with backpressure signaling to prevent memory exhaustion
- **Sampling mode** to throttle backlog growth when system is overwhelmed
- **Fairness**: round-robin or alternating drain across agents
- **Graceful degradation and shutdown**: handling backlog when load normalizes and safely draining on shutdown

## Code Example
```javascript
// Simplified architecture:
// 1. Each agent has a dedicated FIFO buffer
// 2. Global dispatcher reads from buffers in round-robin fashion
// 3. When total backlog exceeds THRESHOLD, enable sampling mode

class EventRouter {
  constructor(workerCount, samplingThreshold, sampleRate) {
    this.agents = new Map();
    this.globalQueue = new BoundedQueue(1000);
    this.workers = new WorkerPool(workerCount);
    this.samplingThreshold = samplingThreshold;
    this.sampleRate = sampleRate; // K
    this.samplingMode = false;
  }

  registerAgent(agentId) {
    this.agents.set(agentId, { buffer: [], paused: false });
  }

  async submit(agentId, event) {
    const agent = this.agents.get(agentId);
    if (!agent) throw new Error(`Unknown agent: ${agentId}`);

    const totalBacklog = this.calculateBacklog();

    if (totalBacklog > this.samplingThreshold && !this.samplingMode) {
      this.samplingMode = true;
    }

    if (this.samplingMode) {
      if (this.sampleCounter++ % this.sampleRate === 0) {
        await this.globalQueue.offer(event);
      } else {
        agent.buffer.push(event);
      }
    } else {
      agent.buffer.push(event);
    }
  }

  calculateBacklog() {
    return Array.from(this.agents.values())
      .reduce((sum, a) => sum + a.buffer.length, 0);
  }

  // Graceful fallback: resume queued events when backlog recedes
  maybeExitSamplingMode() {
    if (this.samplingMode && this.calculateBacklog() < this.samplingThreshold * 0.5) {
      this.samplingMode = false;
      this.drainQueuedEvents();
    }
  }
}
```

## Test Plan

### 1. Per-Agent Ordering Test
- Register 3 agents (A, B, C)
- Submit events in order: A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, B3, C1, C2, C3
- Verify output preserves per-agent sequence: A events arrive in order, same for B and C
- Run 1000 iterations with different submission patterns

### 2. Sampling Accuracy Test
- Set sampleRate = 10 (forward every 10th event)
- Submit 1000 events from a single agent
- Verify ~100 events forwarded immediately, ~900 queued
- Confirm queued events are forwarded after sampling mode exits

### 3. Backpressure Test
- Fill buffers to capacity
- Verify submit() blocks or rejects when queue is full
- Verify memory stays bounded under load

### 4. Fairness Test
- Submit 1000 events each from 5 agents
- Verify no agent is starved (each gets processed)
- Measure inter-arrival times between agents

### 5. Shutdown Test
- Start router with pending events in buffers
- Initiate graceful shutdown
- Verify all in-flight events complete
- Verify no events are lost

